  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2602.16080v1</id>
    <title>Surgical Activation Steering via Generative Causal Mediation</title>
    <updated>2026-02-17T23:13:18Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.16080v1" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.16080v1" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>Where should we intervene in a language model (LM) to control behaviors that are diffused across many tokens of a long-form response? We introduce Generative Causal Mediation (GCM), a procedure for selecting model components, e.g., attention heads, to steer a binary concept (e.g., talk in verse vs. talk in prose) from contrastive long-form responses. In GCM, we first construct a dataset of contrasting inputs and responses. Then, we quantify how individual model components mediate the contrastive concept and select the strongest mediators for steering. We evaluate GCM on three tasks--refusal, sycophancy, and style transfer--across three language models. GCM successfully localizes concepts expressed in long-form responses and consistently outperforms correlational probe-based baselines when steering with a sparse set of attention heads. Together, these results demonstrate that GCM provides an effective approach for localizing and controlling the long-form responses of LMs.</summary>
